The journalist is squinting painfully, holding her notebook three inches from her nose. She trips over a loose floorboard as she enters.
Bea: "Damn this humidity. My eyes are straining, Mr. Jacques. I can’t distinguish my own handwriting. I refuse to wear spectacles—they make a woman look weak in my profession. I need to see clearly to finish my exposé on you."
Voudou Jacques: "You wish to spy on the spirits, but you cannot even see your own feet? Irony is a cruel mistress, Miss Albright."
Bea: "Just fix it. Do you have drops? A salve?"
Voudou Jacques: "For the eyes that are dim, we borrow from the king of the sky. I have a preparation of Eagle’s Eyeball steeped in rainwater caught during a lightning storm. Two drops in each eye. It will burn, but when you open them, you will see a gnat on a leaf at fifty paces. Just be careful you do not see things you wish you hadn't."
